post_text: Our accessibility sidewalk to our ECFE playground was installed this afternoon. Moose Lake School is in need of a paraprofessional that will work 1:1 with students with physical or other disabilities. This position will also include help with personal functions such as feeding and toileting. Applicant is required to be able to lift at least 50 pounds. The successful candidate will have their PCA certification or the ability to obtain it.

Position is open until filled. Interested applicants should complete the application found at this link and return it to the district office for consideration.
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1bGn7DhEkMSMOxq7GXSX2YByXGml9tYC6FJwAHwbxTxg/edit

Applications submitted via Facebook will not be reviewed.

If you have any questions, please contact Kraig Konietzko, Moose Lake Elementary Principal, at 218-485-4435 x1116.

post_text: The Coronavirus continues to impact our communities in many ways. If you need assistance with food, there are opportunities to get the nutritious food your family needs to stay healthy. If you have children and were receiving SNAP or MFIP as of March 18, 2020, you will receive an automatic benefit on your EBT card. If you weren’t receiving SNAP or MFIP but your child was receiving free or reduced lunch, you can apply for P-EBT to help buy food for your family: www.mn.p-ebt.org
shared_text:
MN.P-EBT.ORG
Apply for P-EBT (Pandemic EBT)
text:
The Coronavirus continues to impact our communities in many ways. If you need assistance with food, there are opportunities to get the nutritious food your family needs to stay healthy. If you have children and were receiving SNAP or MFIP as of March 18, 2020, you will receive an automatic benefit on your EBT card. If you weren’t receiving SNAP or MFIP but your child was receiving free or reduced lunch, you can apply for P-EBT to help buy food for your family: www.mn.p-ebt.org

MN.P-EBT.ORG
Apply for P-EBT (Pandemic EBT)

shared_text:
Minnesota School Counselor Association
July 13 at 10:27 AM ·

Over the past few weeks, school counselors have been at the forefront of discussing the needs our students as it relates to distance learning and the continued need for additional funding for student mental health and school counseling services. We were invited by Representative Yoaukim (DFL-Hopkins), the Chair of the Education Policy Committee to meeting to discuss these priorities and were also invited to provide testimony in front of a joint meeting of the House Education Finance and House Education Policy Committees. Thank you Tanis Henderson, Kelsey Clark, and Jillian Smith for helping promote MSCA’s priorities and helping legislators further understand student needs.

post_text:
Congratulations to Jason Schnoll and Luisa Pierce who were recently approved to teach College in the Schools (CITS) courses through UMD at Moose Lake High School next year! Mrs. Pierce will be teaching Spanish III and students will earn UMD credit in SPAN 1102, Beginning Spanish II and SPAN 1201, Intermediate Spanish. Mr. Schnoll will be teaching Physics and students in that course will earn UMD credit in PHYS 1001, Introduction to Physics.

UMD has high standards for their College in the Schools programs. These instructors completed a rigorous application and review process to be approved for these courses. We are thrilled to be able to increase and improve our CITS offerings at MLHS!

post_text:
This last weekend the State History Day Competition was held virtually and we would like to congratulate Emma Steen and Wina Vander Heyden on receiving a topical prize from the University of Minnesota's Center for Austrian Studies for their documentary, "Maria Theresia von Paradis: The Blind Enchantress." Their documentary featured von Paradis, a blind female composer from Austria and was a perfect topic for this year's theme: Breaking Barriers. Congratulations again ladies, we are so proud of the work you did!
Check out their documentary via the link below:
https://youtu.be/4iUTDnKSDSc

post_text:
Thank you to all the parents who took time to fill out our distance learning feedback survey. We heard you and thank you for your input!

Parents of 7-12th graders, many of you asked for a way that you could know what your child is working on. Google Classroom enables us to invite parents so they receive either daily or weekly summaries for your child's classes.

You may be getting invitations to get Google Classroom email summaries for your child(ren). Please open the email(s) and accept the invitation(s). You will then be brought to a screen asking you how often you would like to receive an email summary of your student's activities. You can select weekly, daily, or no summaries.

If you are not getting an email about your child, we may not have a current email address in our system. Please contact allysha.sample@isd97.org if that is the case so we can update your contact information.

Have a great weekend!

April 1 at 12:00 PM ·

Minnesota students, this is not the spring we thought we would have with you. However, in these times filled with change we remain committed to you and your learning. post_text:
This was the first week of distance learning. We are all learning together. If you have questions or concerns you may direct the initial questions to your child's teacher. There will still be people in the office if you have additional needs.

Because of the large numbers of meals and assignments that we are delivering, it would be helpful if each family would place a weatherproof container at the end of their driveway with your child's name clearly labeled on the lid. This will create a more efficient way to deliver the meals and assignments. Many driveways are soft and this is creating problems for the drivers. In addition, this will give your family and our drivers another level of protection with social distancing.

If you need internet to access the online content, you may drive in the bus parking to connect with our guest wifi network from the warmth of your vehicle. Just park as close to building as you can without going on the sidewalk.

Thank you your understanding!

--
Robert Indihar
Superintendent

post_text:
Thank you to everyone who participated in our blood drive last week. Here is a message from the Memorial Blood Centers:

Hello,

Your blood drive is already helping patients in need. Blood donors are truly special people for giving of themselves so that others might live. We truly appreciate your efforts and please extend a big thank you to everyone who donated!

Results

Registered 34

Deferred 2

Drive goal 24

Units collected 37

Number of lives potentially saved! 111

Did you know that Memorial Blood Centers is a local non-profit organization? We are the sole supplier of blood products to 19 hospitals in Northern Minnesota and Northwestern Wisconsin. We also supply both air ambulance services in the state of Minnesota. Thank you for saving lives in your community!

post_text: Starting tomorrow, March 19th, we will be adding free bagged meal delivery for children age 18 and younger to your doorstep if you would like. The only thing we need from you is your consent to let us drop off the food at your house. Please send an email to shari.anderson@isd97.org with your consent if you would like this service. We will still do curbside pick up at the school if that is the method you prefer. Please spread the word that we are providing free lunch and breakfast regardless of your family income. This federally funded program is intended to help all families during this time of national emergency.

post_text:
BREAKING NEWS: Governor Walz has ordered the closure of all schools in Minnesota beginning March 18 through March 27. Our administrative staff needs time to look at how we are going to meet the needs of childcare for our first responders and health care workers and will be getting out more information to families as soon as we are able.

Again, this is a school closure from 3/18-3/27, which means there will not be instruction during this time. Our staff will be working during those school closure dates to put together more information about our distance learning plan should we need to close for an extended period of time.

These are unprecedented times and we appreciate your understanding and support. We remain committed to the health and safety of all our students, staff, and community.

Agate Encores
March 13 at 5:02 PM ·

Late this afternoon, we were advised by the Governor’s office and the Department of Health that all concerts with attendance over 250 should be cancelled or postponed. In light of this unprecedented situation, it is with great regret that we must cancel the “Ring of Kerry” concert on Sunday, March 15. We have no idea when this ban will be lifted, so regrettably we are unable to say that the concert will be rescheduled. We were looking forward to sharing our next season with you. Please visit our website soon (www.agateencores.org) and you will be able to see the promotional video. Thank you for your understanding.

Parents of 10-12th graders, your child has an opportunity to
learn about careers in construction at "Construct Tomorrow" field trip on February 26. Permission slips are due to Mrs. Litsey by Monday, February 24.

At this event, students can experience a variety of construction careers through hands on opportunities with local union apprenticeship programs. This is an opportunity for those that are interested in a building and construction trade career to meet with representatives of local union apprenticeship programs in Duluth. Don’t miss this great opportunity to network, and learn about living wage jobs that are vital to the economic growth of our region.

This week was a long and tough for the Lady Rebels but they persevered. Tuesday was a record night for the Rebels as Natalie Mikrot got her 1000th point and the girls set a team record with 16 '3 pointers' in an awesome game against Mesabi East only to lose by about 15. The Rebels had ME on the ropes most of the game but ran out of gas in the 4th quarter. Thursday they lost a tough game against Milaca but never gave up the fight only losing by 2 in the end, but it literally went down to the last second. Friday, the girls were able to get back on track with a 77-52 win against Mora. THESE GIRLS ARE FUN TO WATCH. Come join us on Thursday 12/12 against Barnum in ML. It's sure to be a night to remember! GO REBELS! Next game is 12/10 vs Cromwell/Wright in Cromwell

post_text: Today, MLHS seventh & eighth graders participated in national "Know Your Classmates" day! Know Your Classmates is a national awareness day designed to create and nurture healthy relationships between classmates, particularly focused on middle school students. Students were paired up with the help of some older student volunteers and had to find something they had in common or learn a new thing about their partner that they didn't know before. Each filled out a hand for their partner with their first name and the one thing they learned about them.

post_text: On June 6, twenty-three students and adults from Moose Lake made the long journey to Thailand for two weeks. We started in Bangkok with a boat tour where we were able to see the Reclining Buddha (it was massive!) and sunset from Golden Mountain. From Bangkok we traveled to Ayutthaya, an ancient city and capital of the Kingdom of Siam. It's now a UNESCO World Heritage Site. We explored a floating market, walked along the banks of River Kwai and rode the Death Railway. We learned how silk and paper umbrellas were made in Chiang Mai and spent time in waterfalls at a national park. We learned how to bargain at local markets and ate our fair share of Thai food (including fried bugs, scorpions and frogs!)! One of our favorite experiences was visiting rescued elephants at the Elephant Nature Park in Chiang Mai. We ended our trip walking the beaches in Cha-am. We had the most amazing time learning and experiencing Thai culture and history that not even the extreme heat or humidity could stop us! It was truly fantastic. Lookout for details this fall on where we're headed next!

From Bangkok we traveled to Ayutthaya, an ancient city and capital of the Kingdom of Siam. It's now a UNESCO World Heritage Site. We explored a floating market, walked along the banks of River Kwai and rode the Death Railway. We learned how silk and paper umbrellas were made in Chiang Mai and spent time in waterfalls at a national park. We learned how to bargain at local markets and ate our fair share of Thai food (including fried bugs, scorpions and frogs!)! One of our favorite experiences was visiting rescued elephants at the Elephant Nature Park in Chiang Mai. We ended our trip walking the beaches in Cha-am. We had the most amazing time learning and experiencing Thai culture and history that not even the extreme heat or humidity could stop us! It was truly fantastic. Lookout for details this fall on where we're headed next!

Thank you, Mr. Hubred, for sharing your stories and showing our students how much they are loved!

He told stories of how suicides of people he knows has changed his perspective on life, along with a story of 'Who I am Makes a Difference' in which each student received 5 ribbons that were to be passed on to anybody in their lives that have made a difference to them. Each student also received a 1 page handwritten letter from him with all of the positives he sees in them. Thank you, Mr. Hubred, for sharing your stories and showing our students how much they are loved!

post_text: On Friday, May 17th, Kristi Skelton, Elementary Enrichment Coordinator, along with ten 6th grade students participated in the Young Authors/Young Artists Conference at the College of St. Benedict in St. Joseph, MN. Derek Anderson, an award winning author and illustrator with more than 25 books to his credit, was the keynote speaker. He encouraged the students to never give up on their dreams. The students also attended three different break-out sessions of their choice. It was a fun, educational and inspiring day for the students!

Building community and fostering positive relationships are an important part of school. Our high school has had the exciting opportunity to pilot some restorative schools practices in the last few weeks. Restorative practices focus on positively impacting the school climate by building community, repairing relationships, and creating an equitable learning environment for all students. Right now we are piloting a check-in circle in one ninth grade advisory as well as within our special education department. Thank you to Chrissy Gamst and Mickleson Consulting for helping us get started with this program.
All high school staff are being trained in introductory restorative practices during an end of the year staff development day and our implementation team will be working with the trainers to put together an implementation plan for MLHS for the 2019-2020 school year.
